g.text: Archive all of your favorite podcasts
⚠ Deprecated, will be removed in the next major release
Update the feeds with newly added episodes only. Adding episodes ends with the first episode already present in the
Feed URLs to archive. Use repeatedly for multiple feeds.
OPML files containing feed URLs to archive. OPML files can be exported from a variety of podcatchers. Use
Directory to which to download the podcast archive. By default, the archive will be created in the current
Path to a config file. Command line arguments will take precedence.
Location of the database to keep track of downloaded episodes. By default, the database will be created as
'podcast-archiver.db' in the directory of the config file.
Template to be used when generating filenames. Available template variables are: 'episode.title,
Write episode metadata to a .info.json file next to the media file itself.
Format filenames in the most compatible way, replacing all special characters.
Run podcast-archiver continuously. Set to a non-zero number of seconds to sleep after all available
episodes have been downloaded. Otherwise the application exits after all downloads have been completed.
Only download the given number of episodes per podcast feed. Useful if you don't really need the entire
Ignore the episodes database when downloading. This will cause files to be downloaded again, even if
they already exist in the database.
Print only minimal progress information. Errors will always be emitted.
Download only the first 1048576 bytes of episodes for debugging purposes.
Increase the level of verbosity while downloading. Can be passed multiple times. Increased verbosity and
non-interactive execution (in a cronjob, docker compose, etc.) will disable progress bars.
Non-interactive execution also always raises the verbosity unless --quiet is passed.
Emit an example YAML config file to stdout and exit.
